<!-- ════════════ THE PROBLEM ════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="problem">
  <div class="section-label">The Crisis</div>
  <h2>Portland's streets are falling apart, and the current plan to fix them is a head tax</h2>

  <p>PBOT faces a <strong>$6 billion</strong> maintenance backlog. Gas tax revenue is declining. The bureau can barely keep staff on payroll, let alone fill potholes. Everyone agrees something must be done.</p>

  <p>The proposed Transportation Utility Fee would charge every single-family household $12/month and every apartment dweller $8.40/month—a flat per-unit charge regardless of income, car ownership, or how much you actually use the road network.</p>

  <div class="callout warning">
    <div class="callout-title">The core problem</div>
    <p>A flat per-unit fee is a <strong>head tax</strong>. A single mother taking the bus pays the same as a two-car household. A studio apartment renter pays $8.40; a homeowner on a 10,000-square-foot lot pays $12. When the fee is measured per acre of land consumed, apartment dwellers pay <strong>up to 600% more</strong> than large-lot homeowners.</p>
  </div>

  <p>We've seen this movie before. The Portland Arts Tax—another flat head tax—has become an administrative nightmare with dismal collection rates and perpetual public resentment. The TUF as proposed risks the same fate, with the added problem of being economically distortionary.</p>
</section>

<hr class="section-divider">

<!-- ════════════ DIAGNOSIS ════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="diagnosis">
  <div class="section-label">The Diagnosis</div>
  <h2>Head taxes are bad policy. But so is trying to make the fee itself do redistributive work.</h2>

  <p>Some proposals would scale the TUF by lot size, charging more for larger parcels. The instinct is right—large lots consume more public infrastructure. But there are two problems:</p>

  <div class="principle">
    <div class="principle-icon">1</div>
    <div class="principle-content">
      <h4>The market already prices density</h4>
      <p>If you live in a 20-unit building, you're already paying roughly 1/20th the land cost of a single-family homeowner on the same parcel. The price system has already rewarded your efficient land use through lower housing costs. A density-scaled TUF double-counts that benefit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="principle">
    <div class="principle-icon">2</div>
    <div class="principle-content">
      <h4>Lot size doesn't cause road damage</h4>
      <p>A 10,000 sq ft lot doesn't generate twice the road wear of a 5,000 sq ft lot. <em>Driving</em> causes road damage—vehicle miles traveled, vehicle weight, tire type. A lot-size fee looks like an efficiency improvement, but it's pricing the wrong thing. It's addressing a cost-allocation problem, not correcting an externality.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="principle">
    <div class="principle-icon">3</div>
    <div class="principle-content">
      <h4>It's legally vulnerable</h4>
      <p>Oregon's Measure 5/50 caps property taxes. A fee scaled to lot area is substantially correlated with land value—a plaintiff could argue it's a property tax with extra steps. Flat per-unit fees have survived legal challenge in 31 Oregon cities. Lot-area fees have not been tested.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <blockquote>
    The instrument of revenue collection and the instrument of redistribution should be separate. Collect efficiently. Redistribute universally.
    <cite>— The foundational insight of optimal tax theory</cite>
  </blockquote>
</section>

<hr class="section-divider">

<!-- ════════════ THE TWO PROPOSALS ════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="proposals">
  <div class="section-label">The Proposals</div>
  <h2>Two policies, two problems, zero means tests</h2>

  <p>Instead of one fee trying to do everything—fund roads, price driving, and redistribute—we propose decomposing the problem into two clean instruments, each optimized for its purpose.</p>

  <!-- POLICY 1 -->
  <div class="proposal-card green">
    <div class="proposal-number">01</div>
    <h3>Price Parking, Not People</h3>
    <div class="subtitle">The Efficiency Instrument</div>

    <p>Dramatically expand demand-responsive parking pricing across Portland. This is the closest thing to congestion pricing the city can implement <em>today</em>, without state authorization.</p>

    <p>Free on-street parking is a <strong>massive in-kind subsidy</strong> to car owners—and in-kind subsidies create deadweight loss by definition. When you give away a scarce public resource (street space) for free, you guarantee it will be misallocated. Demand-responsive pricing fixes this.</p>

    <p>The late Donald Shoup—widely revered in urbanist and progressive policy circles—spent a career demonstrating that parking pricing is one of the most efficient and equitable transportation policies a city can adopt. Portland already uses demand-responsive meters in some districts. The proposal is simply to extend the principle citywide.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="callout-title">Why this is a near-perfect Pigouvian price</div>
      <p>You are charging for the direct use of a specific piece of transportation infrastructure, in real time. The nexus is airtight—legally bulletproof. The supply of street space is fixed (perfectly inelastic), so the fee creates <strong>approximately zero deadweight loss</strong>. And because the fee falls only on those who choose to store a private vehicle in public space, it provides a powerful signal to shift to transit, biking, and walking.</p>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Crucially, this captures non-residents.</strong> Joe Cortright has documented that the majority of vehicle traffic damaging Portland streets originates outside the city. The TUF can never touch those drivers. Parking pricing can.</p>

    <p>Additional measures within council authority: a per-delivery fee on e-commerce shipments (already floated by PBOT at 25–50¢/delivery, raising $5–9M/year) and a priced residential parking permit program scaled to the number of vehicles registered at each address.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- POLICY 2 -->
  <div class="proposal-card terra">
    <div class="proposal-number">02</div>
    <h3>Flat Fee + Universal Credit</h3>
    <div class="subtitle">The Revenue &amp; Equity Instrument</div>

    <p>Keep the TUF as a flat per-unit fee—simple, legally tested, easy to administer. But set the rate somewhat higher than currently proposed, and use the additional revenue to fund a <strong>universal per-person annual credit</strong> paid to every Portland adult.</p>

    <p>The credit is not means-tested. Everyone gets it. But because it's a fixed dollar amount, it's worth proportionally more to lower-income residents. Combined with the flat fee, the <strong>effective rate is automatically progressive</strong>—no eligibility determination, no bureaucratic apparatus, no arts-tax-style collection nightmare.</p>

    <div class="callout gold">
      <div class="callout-title">Implementation</div>
      <p>The universal credit can be delivered through the same infrastructure the city already uses for the Arts Tax—the same database of Portland adult residents, the same payment mechanism. You don't touch the Arts Tax itself. You simply run a second program through the same pipe, in the opposite direction. The Arts Tax charges every adult $35/year. The universal credit <em>pays</em> every adult, say, $100/year. Net effect: Portlanders are $65/year ahead, the Arts Tax is functionally more than offset, and the system is progressive by construction.</p>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

