<!-- ════════════ THE MATH ════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="math">
  <div class="section-label">The Numbers</div>
  <h2>How the effective rate becomes progressive</h2>

  <p>Consider a scenario where the TUF is set at $16/month for single-family homes and $11/month for apartments, with a $100/year universal credit to every adult.</p>

  <div class="math-block">
    <span class="label">Effective Annual Cost by Household Type</span>
    <span class="dim">───────────────────────────────────────────</span>
    <br>
    <span class="accent">Low-income apartment renter (1 adult)</span>
    <br>
    &nbsp; Fee: $11 × 12 = <span class="highlight">$132</span>/yr
    <br>
    &nbsp; Credit: <span class="highlight">−$100</span>/yr
    <br>
    &nbsp; Net: <span class="highlight">$32/yr</span> <span class="dim">($2.67/mo)</span>
    <br><br>
    <span class="accent">Couple in apartment (2 adults)</span>
    <br>
    &nbsp; Fee: $11 × 12 = <span class="highlight">$132</span>/yr
    <br>
    &nbsp; Credit: <span class="highlight">−$200</span>/yr
    <br>
    &nbsp; Net: <span class="highlight">−$68/yr</span> <span class="dim">(net positive $5.67/mo)</span>
    <br><br>
    <span class="accent">Single-family homeowner (2 adults)</span>
    <br>
    &nbsp; Fee: $16 × 12 = <span class="highlight">$192</span>/yr
    <br>
    &nbsp; Credit: <span class="highlight">−$200</span>/yr
    <br>
    &nbsp; Net: <span class="highlight">−$8/yr</span> <span class="dim">(approximately break-even)</span>
    <br><br>
    <span class="accent">High-income homeowner, large lot (2 adults)</span>
    <br>
    &nbsp; Fee: $16 × 12 = <span class="highlight">$192</span>/yr
    <br>
    &nbsp; Parking costs: <span class="highlight">~$300–600</span>/yr <span class="dim">(2 vehicles)</span>
    <br>
    &nbsp; Credit: <span class="highlight">−$200</span>/yr
    <br>
    &nbsp; Net: <span class="highlight">$292–592/yr</span>
    <br>
    <span class="dim">───────────────────────────────────────────</span>
  </div>

  <p>The progressivity emerges from three forces working together: the flat credit is worth proportionally more at lower incomes, multi-adult households benefit more from the per-person credit, and the parking pricing falls exclusively on driving behavior.</p>

  <table class="compare-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Household</th>
        <th>Current TUF Proposal</th>
