<!-- ════════════ FAQ / OBJECTIONS ════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="faq">
  <div class="section-label">Addressing Concerns</div>
  <h2>Doesn't this hurt people who have no choice but to drive?</h2>

  <p>This is the most important objection, and the answer is: <em>that's what the universal credit is for.</em> A resident in outer East Portland with limited transit options who must drive to work will pay parking fees when they park in metered areas—but they receive the full universal credit. For most moderate-income households, the credit more than offsets the new parking costs. The framework doesn't assume everyone can stop driving. It just ensures that the <em>price signal</em> exists, while the <em>redistribution</em> cushions its impact on those with fewer choices.</p>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 48px;">PBOT needs money <em>now</em>. Isn't this too complicated?</h2>

  <p>The two policies operate on different timelines. The flat TUF can pass immediately—council has the authority, PBOT gets funded, the emergency is addressed. Expanded parking pricing and the universal credit can be developed in parallel and implemented over the following months. The urgent need for revenue is not a reason to lock in a bad fee structure permanently. Pass the simple flat TUF now; improve the system as soon as the parking and credit mechanisms are ready.</p>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 48px;">Is the parking expansion politically feasible?</h2>

  <p>Portland already has metered parking and demand-responsive pricing in several districts. This isn't a novel concept—it's extending an existing, accepted practice. The revenue goes directly to road maintenance that every resident wants. And the Shoup framework has broad support across the urbanist spectrum, from market urbanists to democratic socialists. Councilor Green is ideally positioned to champion this—reclaiming public space from private vehicles and redirecting the value back to the public is a message that resonates deeply with his base.</p>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 48px;">What about the first-best policies we can't do?</h2>

  <p>Let's name them honestly: a proper land value tax replacing Oregon's broken property tax system, a VMT charge weighted by vehicle weight, and a statewide universal basic income. All of these require state-level action. Portland's council should publicly advocate for Measure 5/50 reform and state VMT pricing—and should design the TUF and parking pricing to be <em>superseded</em> by those better instruments if and when they arrive. In the meantime, the framework proposed here is the best achievable second-best policy: it approximates the right price signals, achieves progressive redistribution, and stays within the city's legal authority.</p>
</section>

